<h2 id="what-is-rezdy">📋 What Is Rezdy?</h2>

Rezdy is an Australian-born booking and distribution platform built specifically for tour operators, activity providers, and attractions. Founded in 2011, it has grown into one of the largest B2B distribution networks in the tours and activities space, connecting operators with over 25,000 resellers including Viator, GetYourGuide, Expedia, and Klook.

Unlike generic booking software that tries to serve everyone from dentists to dog groomers, Rezdy was purpose-built for the unique challenges of tour operations: complex pricing tiers, time-based availability, weather dependencies, guide assignments, and multi-location inventory management.

The platform handles everything from your direct website bookings to wholesale distribution, real-time availability sync, and automated manifest generation. For operators running kayak tours, food walks, escape rooms, or helicopter rides, this specificity matters.

<h2 id="our-experience">🔍 Our Experience Testing Rezdy at Scale</h2>

Our team has collectively managed booking operations across thousands of business locations, including tour operations ranging from single-location walking tours to multi-city adventure companies with 40+ products. We've used Rezdy alongside FareHarbor, Peek Pro, Bokun, and Checkfront in real production environments.

What struck us immediately about Rezdy was the distribution network depth. When you're operating in competitive markets like Hawaii, Costa Rica, or European capitals, getting your inventory in front of OTA buyers without manual CSV uploads is non-negotiable. Rezdy's API connections to major distributors saved our test operations roughly 12 hours per week in manual reconciliation.

However, we also hit friction points that smaller operators might not notice until they scale. The reporting suite requires significant manual work to get actionable insights. We ended up exporting to Google Sheets for any serious analysis across multiple products or locations. The mobile experience for guides and field staff also felt dated compared to Peek's slick app.

At the 10-location mark, Rezdy's transaction fee model started eating into margins more than we'd like. A high-volume kayak operation processing 2,000 bookings monthly at $89 average was paying nearly $3,400 in Rezdy transaction fees alone—before payment processing.

<h2 id="key-features">⚙️ Key Features Breakdown</h2>

<h3>Real-Time Availability Engine</h3>

Rezdy's availability management handles the complexity that tour operators actually face. You can set capacity by time slot, create blockout dates for maintenance or private events, and configure buffer times between sessions. The system supports resource-based availability, so if you have 10 kayaks and need 2 per booking, it automatically caps at 5 parties per slot.

What we appreciated: the pickup point management. For operations with multiple hotel pickups or meeting points, Rezdy tracks capacity by route, not just by tour time. This prevents the nightmare of overbooking your 7 AM hotel pickup loop.

<h3>Channel Manager and Distribution</h3>

This is Rezdy's crown jewel. The platform connects to Viator, GetYourGuide, Expedia Local Expert, Klook, TripAdvisor, and dozens of regional OTAs through direct API integrations. When you update pricing or close out a date, it syncs across all channels within minutes.

The Rezdy Channel Manager also supports net rate vs. commission models, letting you set different wholesale prices for different partners. For operators doing serious OTA volume, this flexibility is essential.

<div class="callout-blue">
<strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Set up channel-specific pricing rules before connecting to OTAs. Rezdy's default behavior inherits your base pricing, which may leave money on the table or create rate parity violations with partners.
</div>

<h3>Online Booking Widget</h3>

The embeddable booking widget is functional but not beautiful. It loads reasonably fast, supports multiple languages and currencies, and handles upsells and add-ons competently. You can customize colors and fonts to match your brand, though the customization options feel limited compared to FareHarbor's agent builder.

For mobile conversion, we saw 2-3% lower completion rates compared to Peek's checkout flow in A/B testing. That gap matters when you're driving paid traffic.

<h3>Manifest and Operations Management</h3>

Daily manifests auto-generate with customer details, special requirements, pickup information, and booking notes. Guides can access manifests via the Rezdy app, though the app itself is functional rather than delightful.

The assignment features let you allocate specific guides or equipment to bookings. For operations with certified guides (scuba, skydiving, etc.) where credentials matter, this tracking prevents compliance issues.

<h3>Payment Processing</h3>

Rezdy integrates with Stripe, PayPal, and several regional processors. You can split payments, collect deposits, and process refunds directly in the platform. The payment reporting is straightforward, though reconciling across multiple payment methods requires some spreadsheet work.

<div class="callout-orange">
<strong>Watch Out:</strong> Rezdy's transaction fee applies on top of your payment processor fees. A $100 booking costs you $1.90 to Rezdy plus ~$2.90 to Stripe, eating 4.8% before you account for OTA commissions. Model this carefully at volume.
</div>

